'''Connected health''' is a socio-technical model for healthcare management and delivery<ref>Carroll, N. [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/7742288/?reload=true (2016). Key Success Factors for Smart and Connected Health Software Solutions.] Computer, 49(11), 22-28.</ref> by using technology to provide healthcare services remotely. Connected health, also known as technology enabled care (TEC) aims to maximize healthcare resources and provide increased, flexible opportunities for consumers to engage with clinicians and better self-manage their care<ref>[https://journal.gerontechnology.org/archives/1ba3458ec8804567960527b75927f0a4.pdf N. Carroll, C. Kennedy, & I. Richardson (2016). Connected Community Healthcare Ecosystem (CCHE) for managing long-term conditions. Gerontechnology, 14(2):64-77 doi: https://dx.doi.org/10.4017/gt.2016.14.2.003.00]</ref>. It uses readily available consumer technologies to deliver patient care outside of the hospital or doctor's office. Connected health encompasses programs in telehealth, remote care (such as home care) and disease and lifestyle management, often leverages existing technologies such as connected devices using cellular networks and is associated with efforts to improve chronic care.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
The United States and European Union are two dominant markets for the use of connected health in home care service, in part due to the high availability of telephone and Internet service as compared to other parts of the world.{{cn|date=December 2017}} Proponents of connected health believe that technology can transform healthcare delivery and address inefficiencies especially in the area of work flow management, chronic disease management and [[patient compliance]] of the US and global healthcare systems.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==History== Connected health has its roots in [[telemedicine]], and its more recent relative, [[telehealth]]. The first telemedicine programs were primarily undertaken to address healthcare access and/or provider shortages. Connected health is distinguished from telemedicine by:{{cn|date=December 2017}}
* A broader concern for healthcare cost, quality and efficiency, particularly as related to the chronically ill * Concomitant interests in making healthcare more patient centric by promoting healthcare consumerism through education, and patient feedback * Efforts in the direction of integrating data generated outside of traditional healthcare settings such as the home with centralised, often [[electronic patient record]]
== Definition == There is no standard, accepted definition of connected health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.connectedhealthireland.com/what-is-connected-health/|title=Definition of Connected Health, e-health, m-health, tele-|website=Connected Health Ireland|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-18}}</ref> On a broader note, connected health is the "umbrella term arrived to lessen the confusion over the definitions of telemedicine, telehealth and mhealth".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Iglehart|first=John K.|date=2014-02-01|title=Connected health: emerging disruptive technologies|journal=Health Affairs (Project Hope)|volume=33|issue=2|pages=190|doi=10.1377/hlthaff.2014.0042|issn=1544-5208|pmid=24493758}}</ref> It is considered as the new lexicon for the term telemedicine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barr|first=Paul J.|last2=McElnay|first2=James C.|last3=Hughes|first3=Carmel M.|date=2012-02-01|title=Connected health care: the future of health care and the role of the pharmacist|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1365-2753.2010.01522.x/abstract|journal=Journal of Evaluation in Clinical Practice|language=en|volume=18|issue=1|pages=56–62|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2753.2010.01522.x|pmid=20698917|issn=1365-2753}}</ref> The technology view of connected health focuses more on the connection methods between clients and the health care professional.
An alternative view is that of a socio-technical perspective in which connected health is considered as a combination of people, processes and technology. In 2015 Connected health was defined as patient-centred care resulting from process-driven health care delivery undertaken by health care professionals, patients and/or carer who are supported by the use of technology (software and/or hardware).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lero.ie/sites/default/files/Lero-TR-2015-03%20Connected%20Health.pdf|title=Connected Health: People, Technology and Processes| last=Richardson| first=Ita| date=2015| website=Lero – the Irish Software Research Centre|publisher=www.lero.ie|access-date=April 19, 2016}}</ref>
==In operation== Two "core platforms" are emphasized in connected health, self-care and remote care, with programs primarily focused on monitoring and feedback for the chronically ill, elderly, and those patients located at an untenable distance from primary or specialty providers.{{cn|date=December 2017}} Programs designed to improve patient-provider communication within an individual medical practice for example, the use of email to communicate with patients between office visits also fall within the purview of connected health.{{cn|date=December 2017}} There are also [[lifestyle coaching]] programs, in which an individual receives healthcare information to facilitate behavior change to improve their fitness and/or general well being, (see [[Wellness (alternative medicine)|wellness]]) or to reduce or eliminate the impact of a particular behavior that presents a risk to their health status.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=6345919&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fxpls%2Fabs_all.jsp%3Farnumber%3D6345919|title=Radar walking speed measurements of seniors in their apartments: Technology for fall prevention|publisher=IEEE EMBC 2012}}</ref> Some of the most common types of connected health programs in operation today include:
* Home care via remote monitoring of chronically ill patients including surveillance connected devices or patient controlled monitoring of health parameters{{cn|date=December 2017}} * Traditional [[telehealth]] programs, where care is provided in remote areas by teams of local clinicians or community healthcare workers teamed up with specialists in medical centers{{cn|date=December 2017}} * Monitoring programs whose aim is to ensure the safety and quality of life of elderly parents living at a distance from their relatives{{cn|date=December 2017}} * Web-based second opinion services for patients in need of medical care{{cn|date=December 2017}} * Lifestyle and fitness coaching for wellness or health risk reduction{{cn|date=December 2017}}
The Center for Connected Health is implementing a range of programs in high-risk, chronic and remotely located populations.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
Inherent in the concept of connected health is flexibility in terms of technological approaches to care delivery and specific program objectives. For instance, remote monitoring programs might use a combination of cell phone and smart phone technology, online communications or biosensors and may aim to increase patient-provider communication, involve patients in their care through regular feedback, or improve upon a health outcome measure in a defined patient population or individual. Digital pen technology, global positioning, videoconferencing and environmental sensors are all playing a role in connected health.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==Goals== {{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}} Proponents of Connected health view it as a critical component of change in human healthcare and envision:
* Reductions in the cost of providing quality care to the chronically ill, estimated by the Center for Health Care Economics at the Milken Institute to be over $1 trillion per year * Improved global and local [[public health surveillance]], with a resultant reduction in epidemics, increased control over infectious disease and improved drug safety * Diminished rate of medical errors * Better "customer service" in healthcare * Ongoing preventive health, with attendant reductions in: morbidity, mortality and the cost of care * Consumer engagement in health and self-management * Safer and more effective clinical trials
==Evolution== {{off-topic|date=December 2017}} Rising costs, increases in chronic diseases, geographic dispersion of families, growing provider shortages, ethnic disparities in care, better survival rates among patients fighting serious diseases, an aging U.S. population and longer lifespan are all factors pointing to a need for better ways of delivering healthcare.<ref>[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/18802 "The Health Care Crisis and What to Do About It"], The New York Review of Books website, (Accessed December 10, 2008)</ref><ref>[http://www.americansforhealthcare.org/facts/ Americans for Healthcare website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705134639/http://www.americansforhealthcare.org/facts/ |date=2008-07-05 }}(Accessed December 10, 2008)</ref><ref>[http://www.ahrq.gov/news/ulp/costs/ulpcosts1.htm "Health Care Costs: Why Do They Increase? What Can We Do?"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205100938/http://www.ahrq.gov/news/ulp/costs/ulpcosts1.htm |date=2008-12-05 }}, Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality website, (Accessed December 10, 2008)</ref>
[[Direct-to-consumer advertising]] is a demonstrated contributor to the rise in consumer demand, as is the mass availability of inexpensive technology and ubiquity of the Internet, cell phones and PDAs.<ref>PriceWaterhouseCoopers. 2006. The Factors Fueling Rising Healthcare Costs 2006, Prepared for America's Health Insurance Plans, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.kff.org/insurance/snapshot/chcm030807oth.cfm "How Changes in Medical Technology Affect Health Care Costs"] Kaiser Family Foundation website, March 2007 (Accessed December 10, 2008)</ref> Connected health experts such as Joseph C. Kvedar, believe that consumer engagement in healthcare is on its way to becoming a major force for change.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
In summary, connected health has arisen from: 1) a desire on the part of individual physicians and healthcare organizations to provide better access, quality and efficiency of care 2) dynamics of the healthcare economy (such as rising costs and changing demographics) 3) consumerism in health care and a drive towards patient centric healthcare. Together, these factors are providing impetus for connected healthcare in the United States and many other industrialised nations and forcing innovation both from within and outside the system.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==Evidence== While connected health is yet emerging, there is evidence of its benefit. For example, in a program being implemented by the Center for Connected Health and Partners Home Care, over 500 heart failure patients have now been monitored remotely through the collection of vital signs, including heart rate, blood pressure and weight, using simple devices in the patient's home. The information is sent daily to a home health nurse, who can identify early warning signs, notify the patient's [[primary care physician]], and intervene to avert potential health crises. A pilot of this program demonstrated reduced hospitalizations.<ref>[http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/334/7600/942 bmj 2007]; 334: 942 (5 may)</ref> Another initiative at the Center for Connected Health uses cellular telephone technology and a "smart" pill bottle to detect when a patient has not taken their scheduled medication. A signal is then sent that lights up an ambient orb device in the patient's home to remind them to take their medication.
==Funding and implementation== It appears that connected health programs are operated and funded primarily by home care agencies and large healthcare systems.{{cn|date=December 2017}} However, insurers and employers are increasingly interested in connected health for its potential to reduce direct and indirect healthcare costs.In 2007, [[EMC Corporation]] launched the first employer-sponsored connected health program, in the beta phase of implementation, aimed at improving outcomes and cost of care for patients with high blood pressure.<ref>[http://www.boston.com/yourlife/health/diseases/articles/2007/03/03/employees_to_get_an_online_checkup/?page=1 Kowalczyk, L. Employees to get an online checkup: Care provider, EMC will test a program to cut health costs], The Boston Globe, March 3, 2007</ref>
==US government agencies== Government agencies involved in connected health include:
* The Office for the Advancement of Telehealth * The [[National Center for Telehealth & Technology]] (T2) * The [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]] (CMS), to the extent that Medicaid reimburses for telemedicine programs, at the state's option. According to the CMS Web site, at least 18 states are allowing reimbursement for services provided via telemedicine for reasons that include improved access to specialists for rural communities and reduced transportation costs. * The [[Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology]] (ONC) is charged with creating an interoperable health information technology infrastructure for the nation, primarily defined as an electronic health records system. Former National Coordinator [[David Brailer]] indicated his support for portable personal health records which are controlled by consumers. As of 2006 it remained to be seen how his successor, Robert Kolodner, will interpret this charge.<ref>Brailer, David J. Your Medical History, To Go. The New York Times. September 19, 2006.</ref>
==Personal health records== Personal health records, or PHRS, (see [[personal health record]]) – are essentially medical records controlled and maintained by the healthcare consumer. PHRs intersect with connected health in that they attempt to increase the involvement of healthcare consumers in their care.<ref>https://thenextweb.com/microsoft/2013/05/11/microsofts-sean-nolan-on-electronic-medical-records-their-storage-and-the-future-of-healing/</ref> By contrast, electronic medical records (EMRs) (see [[electronic medical record]]) are digital medical records or medical records systems maintained by hospitals or medical practices and are not part of connected health delivery.
